\section{Curves and Surfaces}
\label{sec:org3e98e2f}
Given a manifold, we shall be concerned with points in it and subsets of points which define curves and surfaces of different dimensions.
We shall frequently define these curves and surfaces \textbf{parametrically}. Thus , since a curve has one degree of freedom it depends on one
parameter ans so we define a \textbf{curve} by the parametric equations

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:orgb0c764a}
x^{a}=x^{a}(u)\quad (a=1,2,\cdots,n)
\end{equation}

where \(u\) is the parameter and \(x^1(u), x^2(u),...,x^n(u)\) denote \(n\) funcitons of \(u\). Similary, since a \textbf{subspace} or \textbf{surface} of
\(m\) dimensions \((m<n)\) has \(m\) degrees of freedom, it dependes on \(m\) parameters and it is given by the parametric equations


\section{Transformation of coordinates}
\label{sec:org4c4fba5}
\begin{itemize}
\item When we make a statemen about tensors we do not wish it simply to hold just for one coordinate system but rather for \textbf{all} coordinate systems.
\item We need to find out how quantities behave when go from one coordinate system to another one.
\end{itemize}
Consider the \textbf{change of coordinates} \(x^{a}\to x'^{a}\) given by \(n\) equations \[x'^{a}=f^{a}(x^1,x^2,...,x^n\quad (a=1,2,...,n)\] where the
\(f\)'s are \emph{single-valued continuous differentiable functions}, at least for certain ranges of their arguments. We can write \(x'^{a}=f^{a}(x)\).
Furthermore, we can write the equation more simply still as
\begin{equation}\label{5.6}
x'^{a}=x'^{a}(x)
\end{equation}
